No
The direct effect of maternal smoking on infant's birth weight and subsequent infant mortality is separate from the direct effect of the health condition on birth weight and infant mortality. The health condition is unobserved, and its direct effects on birth weight and infant mortality are not dependent on the maternal smoking status. The birth weight, in turn, has a direct effect on infant mortality. The probability of high infant mortality for an infant with a smoking mother is 80%, which is higher than the 46% probability for an infant with a nonsmoking mother. This difference in probability directly results from the direct effect of maternal smoking on birth weight and subsequent infant mortality, rather than any interaction between the health condition and the maternal smoking status.<|eot_id|>
